Metrics of Aging - Phenotypic Aging in BLSA

Perry Kuo, Luigi Ferrucci, Jennifer Schrack, Michelle Shardell, Morgan Levine

14 December 2018

The format is adopted from course led by Dr. Stephanie Hicks

Motivation

With the advent of public health and medical care, the life expetancy has increased over past half century. The society is aging, and there are more and more researchers trying to understand the underlying mechanism why human age, and the potential modifiable facorts to decelerate the aging process. To achieve these goals, some researchers proposed some metrics to capture the functional aging, such as frailty index, and further investigate the relationship between functional aging and disability/mortality. With the hypothesis that functions are especially important for older people and applying potential approaches to improve functions may maximize human’s quality of life and prolong longevity, functional aging has been one of the main foci in geriatric research over past two decades. Consequently, it is of vital importance to understand the drivers of functional declines, which can be potentially measured by changes of phenotypes.

To understand the biological mechanism of aging, several metrics of biological age, such as epigenetic clock, have been proposed. Among these proposed metrics, most of them utilized the data available, and leverage on the dimension reduction tools and choose the statitical model fit the mortality the best as biological age. With lack of a more conceptual and mechanistic framework, these metrics may be useful for mortality or cormorbitidy prediction, but may not be able to capture the earlier change of aging.

Thus, we propose a temporal heirarchy framework for metrics of aging, in which phenotypes serve as the bridge between underlying biological drivers of aging and the functional decline we observe. Earlier this year, the concept has been described by Dr. Luigi Ferrucci et al, and is shown as following:

with proposed measures as following:

With an attempt to understand these temporal heirarchy of aging, in Baltimore Loungitudinal Study of Aging (BLSA), not only the functions, but also the proposed phenotypes were measured within participants with relatively health status when recruited, for the purpose of diminishing the effect of diseases as more as possible.

In this paper, we try to understand:

1. Are the proposed phenotypes appropriate in terms of functional decline?
2. Do the proposed phenotyes within the same domain capture similar properties? And do the prosposed phenotyeps accross different domians capture the construct of aging?

Multidimensional Factor Analysis [Round 1.] - EFA + CFA

  • Plan: Conducting a multidimensional EFA
    Now that we’ve examined the eigenvalues and scree plot to find the data-driven recommended number of factors, we can get down to actually running the multidimensional EFA.

  • Technical Note:
    To run a multidimensional EFA, we need to use the nfactors argument to specify the number of factors desired.

  • Disclaimer:
    Be careful here about the warnings.

  • Try different rotation marix (rotate = “promax”)

  • Interpreting the results
    As we paln, we’ll be interested in items’ factor loadings and individuals’ factor scores. These will be interpreted in the same way, but since now our EFA is multidimensional, we’ll get results for each factor.

  • Note:

  1. An item’s loadings represent the amount of information it provides for each factor. Items’ meaningful loadings will be displayed in the output.

  2. We’ll notice that many items load onto more than one factor, which means they provide information about multiple factors. This may not be desirable for measure development, so sometimes we may consider only the strongest loading for each item.

  3. Each participant will have a factor score for each factor, so that the matrix won’t include blanks. However, participants with missing data will receive NA scores on all factors.

  • Now, take a look at the loadings:

  • Take a look at the loadings (rotate = “promax”)

  • View the first few lines of participants’ factor scores

  • How about comparing our proposed domains with these 5-factor from data-driven approach?
  1. This on our way to model selection.

  2. FOr the purpose of model comparison, there are some commonly used statistics. The TLI is above the 0.90 cutoff for good fit, and the RMSEA is below the 0.05 cutoff for good fit.

  3. Now use our knowledge of finding and interpreting absolute and relative model fit statistics to select the best model for our data.

  4. When we introduced this dataset we said that the items were theorized to load onto four domains, but we may have noticed that our scree plot indicated five factors. We might be wondering which we should trust. We may use fit statistics to make an empirical decision about how many factors to use.

  • Process:
  1. First, we’ll use the pai_EFA dataset to run EFAs with each of the hypothesized number of factors. Then, we can look at the BIC, which is a relative fit statistic, to compare models. (Note: the lowest BIC is preferred!)
  • Here, it seems like our four-domain function better, but this may be by chance.
